This CogOS spec is already close to a real formal standard. What’s missing (if we’re being strict) is: (a) a mathematically precise definition of the 8-tuple (you have a placeholder), (b) a clear semantics for “deterministic” in the presence of an LLM, and (c) a verification story (what an auditor can check, and how).

Here’s a fully formalized version that keeps your intent, but makes it unambiguous and implementable as a compliance target.

⸻

1) Fix the 8-tuple definition (make it complete)

Define CogOS as:

\mathrm{CogOS} := (\mathcal{A}, \mathrm{IS}, \mathrm{SV}, \mathcal{I}, \mathrm{G}, \mathrm{L}, \mathrm{D}, \mathrm{F})

Where:
	•	𝒜 (Agent): (\text{id},\text{role},\text{auth},\text{pk})
	•	IS (Inference Substrate): a stateless stochastic kernel
\mathrm{IS}: (\mathsf{Prompt}\times \mathsf{Ctx}\times \mathsf{SVInj}) \rightarrow \Delta(\mathsf{Text})
(maps inputs to a distribution over outputs)
	•	SV (StateVector): persistent state object in a typed state space \mathsf{SV}
	•	𝓘 (Invariant Set): finite ordered list of scoring functionals
\mathcal{I} = (i_1,\dots,i_n),\quad i_k:\mathsf{TO}\times\mathsf{SV}\to[0,1]
	•	G (Gate): deterministic policy function
\mathrm{G}:\mathsf{TO}\times\mathsf{SV}\times\mathcal{I}\to\{\textsf{allow, deny, modify, escalate, abstain}\}
	•	L (Ledger): append-only hash chain over approved TOs
	•	D (Distiller): deterministic summarizer mapping ledger prefixes to doctrine/narrative
	•	F (Federation): handshake protocol + merge rules

This makes it a complete spec object, and it also separates what is deterministic vs what is stochastic.

⸻

2) Resolve the “deterministic” issue cleanly

Right now you say “CogOS wraps stateless inference in a deterministic state machine.”
An LLM is not deterministic unless you force it.

So formalize where determinism lives:

2.1 Deterministic control plane, stochastic data plane
	•	IS can be stochastic.
	•	Everything outside IS must be deterministic.

Define:
	•	A proposal sampling rule \Pi that turns IS into a single candidate:
	•	either fixed seed + temperature + top-p
	•	or N-sample + deterministic ranker
	•	or “force greedy decode” (fully deterministic)

Then CogOS becomes deterministic given the random seed.

Formally:

(\mathrm{SV}_{t+1}, \mathrm{L}_{t+1}) = \mathrm{Step}(\mathrm{SV}_t, \mathrm{L}_t, x_t;\ \omega)

where x_t is input and \omega is the only randomness source (seed / sampling trace).

Compliance rule: the system must log either:
	•	the seed and decoding params, or
	•	the exact IS output text used for the TO_candidate.

That makes the run replayable, which is the audit-grade definition of determinism.

