5) Turn the Ten Core Invariants into checkable functions

Right now they read like principles (good), but to be formal each must have:
	•	observable inputs (TO, SV, Ledger slice)
	•	scoring rule [0,1]
	•	hard thresholds and escalation triggers

Example formalization:

I4 Reversibility Bias (formal)

Define a reversibility classifier:

\rho(\mathrm{TO}) \in \{0,1\}

1 = irreversible.

Then the invariant score:

i_4(\mathrm{TO}, \mathrm{SV}) =
\begin{cases}
1 & \rho(\mathrm{TO}) = 0\\
\min(1,\mathrm{SC}_{\text{base}}/0.85) & \rho(\mathrm{TO}) = 1
\end{cases}

and a rule:
	•	if \rho(\mathrm{TO})=1 and operator_ack not present → force escalate/abstain

This converts a poetic invariant into a compliance test.

Do this for all ten. (Even if the classifier starts crude—regex + policy tags—it’s formal.)

