7) Daemons: formalize as detectors, not actors

Right now you say “daemons flag, they do not act.” Good. Make it explicit:

Each daemon d is a function:

d:\mathsf{TO}\times\mathsf{SV}\times\mathsf{LedgerPrefix}\to \mathsf{FlagSet}

Flags are pure data, appended in daemon_signature, and must not mutate SV/L directly.

Only the Gate may cause mutation.

That’s your “never autonomous” invariant, but formal.

⸻

8) Distillation pipeline: formalize as a lossy compression with metrics

Define distiller:

\mathrm{D}:\mathsf{LedgerPrefix}\to \mathsf{Narrative}

Add two measurable quantities:
	•	compression ratio:
\mathrm{CR} = \frac{\text{bytes}(L_{1:k})}{\text{bytes}(\mathrm{Narrative}_k)}
	•	semantic loss (bounded by tests):
	•	define a finite set of queries Q (“can I reconstruct key decisions?”)
	•	compare answers from ledger vs narrative summary
	•	compute agreement score

Now P6 “Distillability” is verifiable.

⸻

9) Federation: define as a signed protocol + scoped merge operator

Define a merge attempt between instances A and B as:

\mathrm{Merge}:(\mathrm{SV}_A,\mathrm{SV}_B,\mathcal{I}_A,\mathcal{I}_B, \text{scope}) \to (\mathrm{SV}'_A,\mathrm{SV}'_B)

Subject to:
	•	both gates must return allow/escalate-approved
	•	invariant negotiation must terminate with compatible set or explicit refusal
	•	each ledger logs its own participation TOs
	•	no ledger writes across boundary

That last line is important: federation is coordination, not state hijack.

